Introduction

In this workbook we will play around with various ways to import data into R, and build up our toolset for doing exploratory data analysis (EDA) in R. You should take note of the things that you learn in each EDA step in the various sections, performing similar analysis for the new data sets that we acquire to build up your familiarity with this approach.

If you want to to look up some of the EDA methods we use then a good place to start is R4DS (http://r4ds.had.co.nz/index.html). I suggest you keep a tab open in your browser while you are working through this lesson, exploring related topics and finding out more about the topics that we cover.

I strongly recommend that you play with all of the commands we try out as you go. Copy them across to your own file in RStudio and look them up. Talk to people in your group about it, and see what you can learn from each other. Modify the commands - what do you get? And make sure you save your file! Comment it, so you can remember what you were doing and look back over it again later when you are using similar approaches for your own projects.

First things first lets load the tidyverse (if the below command does not work then you probably need to install the tidyverse first! install.packages("tidyverse") and make sure you do your preparation in the future! Grrrrr)

Ok - lets go get some data!

Option 1: Download a dataset you find from the web and import it to R

There are a lot of sites on the web that have curated sets of data available! Lets go and look at one that can be found on this site: https://ww2.amstat.org/publications/jse/jse_data_archive.htm This site curates lots of different datasets for the purposes of teaching statistics! It has links to the related paper which discusses how the dataset can be used (mainly in minitab which is a very old statistical modelling package - but that does not mean we cant use the data! ;) We are going to use a dataset that has been made available as an .xls file at this link: http://ww2.amstat.org/publications/jse/datasets/kuiper.xls.

Firstly: Download the above file, and put it in the same directory as any R scripts that you are making (or make sure you refer to where you have put it in the read_excel function!) Better still - if you have created a project for that directory then it should show up immediately in your files tab once you have it in the correct directory - see http://r4ds.had.co.nz/workflow-projects.html Projects are definitely the way to go, so if you have not read that chapter of R4DS then I strongly recommend that you do this after today and start using that approach - the downloadable folder of this workbook is an example of a project - have a look at it and try to work out what I did to create it!

We are going to use the readxl package to import this dataset, which is part of the tidyverse (http://readxl.tidyverse.org/).

library(readxl)                     #we need to load this tidyverse package
carPrice<- read_excel("kuiper.xls") #now we just import the dataset and store it 
carPrice

Simple hey? There are lots of other ways to get data. We will return to them in a while, but first lets do a bit of exploratory analysis to find out about our new dataset!

A lightning introduction to Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)

Well.. first things first. What is our variable of interest? This is sometimes called the dependent variable. I think that it should be the Price. We are likely to be trying to work out how Price varies as other things (the explanatory, or independent variables) change. One obvious way in which Price might change would be Mileage right? Both are numeric variables, so the obvious way to have a look at this would be using a scatterplot

ggplot(carPrice) + geom_point(aes(y=Price,x=Mileage))

So interesting, but a bit hard to understand. We can probably do better.

At this point I probably need to point out that tibbles are nice and tidy, but sometimes we want to know the names of all our columns (which is not easy to see using the print method for tibble that we made use of above - mainly because I am lazy and do not like scrolling through the list at the top of the displayed table that we outputted by typing carPrice). Luckily base R has a solution:

Or using another way of getting it (from the tidyverse)

carPrice %>% select(Model)

What is the difference between these?

str(carPrice$Make)
##  chr [1:804] "Buick" "Buick" "Buick" "Buick" "Buick" "Buick" "Buick" ...
is.vector(carPrice$Make)
## [1] TRUE
carPrice %>% select(Model) %>% str
## tibble [804  1] (S3: tbl_df/tbl/data.frame)
##  $ Model: chr [1:804] "Century" "Century" "Century" "Century" ...

So one returns a vector, the other returns a tibble. Different strokes for different folks but this can sometimes be a very important thing to know about in R, as different datatypes can behave very differently with different functions and packages. Can we learn to do things one way only? Not really. In the end you will need to be familiar with both approaches, but for now you should try to do everything you can using the tidyverse as it is much more straightforward. However, you are likely to come across problems that you cannot resolve in the tidyverse, and for that you will need to return to base R, or even use some other package! (See this page about why it is worth teaching the tidyverse first: http://varianceexplained.org/r/teach-tidyverse/ - he convinced me - this is the philosophy we have adopted for this subject!)

Anyhoo after that slight distraction, we were looking at categorical variables. One thing we might want to do is try out a boxplot on these kinds of variables. This gives a nice way to display the distribution of a continuous variable over a set of discrete variables. For example:

ggplot(carPrice) + geom_boxplot(aes(y=Price,x=Type))

So, thinking about what this data means quite a bit of variation of the Price as we vary the Type of car can be seen now. Does this seem right? Arent we leaving an important variable out?

Question: what else in our variable set would be very likely to change the price of a car?

While you are pondering that question, you should think about what the box plots are telling you. Try running ?geom_boxplot and looking at what the help pages tell you. It is essential that you start learning how to read these! So try to work your way through it, even if you find it hard to follow! One strategy that might help could be to google boxplots (or just start with the wikipedia page which has quite a good explanation: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Box_plot).

Make sure you can explain what these things are indicating to someone next to you:

  1. The square bit
  2. The line inside the square
  3. The lines that hang off the square
  4. The dots

Anyhoo back to that question that I asked you above. One thing we would expect to affect sales Price would be the Make of the car! Some brands should be more expensive than others, and it is quite likely that some vary more than others

ggplot(carPrice) + geom_boxplot(aes(y=Price,x=Make))

Right. That seems to be backed up by the boxplot. So there is a variance with both Make and Model just as you would expect. How do they relate to each other? We can add one extra bit to our ggplot call to see this.

ggplot(carPrice) + geom_boxplot(aes(y=Price, x=Type)) + facet_wrap(~Make)

Interesting indeed. Why dont you try explaining what is going on to somebody sitting next to you. You might also want to try doing a similar exploratory trick with some other variables.

One final trick before we move onto getting some more data in a different way. We would expect that these effects might show up in our scatter plot too. How could we show this up?

ggplot(carPrice) + geom_point(aes(y=Price, x=Mileage, color=Make))

Or going a bit more extreme can we get the Model info in as well?

ggplot(carPrice) + geom_point(aes(y=Price, x=Mileage, color=Make, shape=Type))

So there are lots of ways to start working out what is going on in this dataset what else could you try? This is not a particularly readable plot, although it contains quite a bit of information.

Option 2: Read directly from the web

You dont actually have to download the file if you can rely on your data connection.

  • Pro: if the data updates then you will get it automatically.
  • Con: you are going to be downloading that data more than once which can be a bit wasteful (try investigating the cache=TRUE option in Rmd if you want to limit this). You can also find that the data disappears sometimes or changes (Indeed - that happened to me in updating this workbook once! Took ages to get rSDMX working again grumble grumble.)

The choice is yours really - and will probably depend on the situation. I tend to prefer direct fetch from the web as often my datasets get updated, but there are plenty of times when you will not have to do this. Anyway - you should really know how to do it, which goes like this:

#reading in the data using a very easy to use command from the readr package:
physics_grades <- read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/bot13956/datasets/master/introduction_to_physics_grades.csv")
## 
##  Column specification 
## cols(
##   Count = col_double(),
##   Score = col_double(),
##   Grade = col_character()
## )

Note that there is a difference between read_csv (which is from the tidyverse and so returns a tibble) and read.csv (which is from base r and so returns a data.frame). Many pages and books will use read.csv. Go and try it! (You might have to access the help page with ?read.csv to work out how). My recommendation would be to use read_csv wherever you can, as the resulting tibble will work much more nicely with tidyverse packages like ggplot2 and dplyr.

Option 3: Use tools designed to interface with APIs

An excellent place to try getting data from is the various statistics websites that governmental bodies around the world have set up, or using various public APIs released by various social media sites. The most legitimate way to do this is usually via an API (or Application Programming Interface) that they have set up to facilitate this process. These normally run over HTTP, which stands for Hypertext Transfer Protocol. If you dont know anything about that then you should probably go and have a look at one of these quickstart guides:

  • https://zapier.com/learn/apis/chapter-2-protocols/ (more basic)
  • https://code.tutsplus.com/tutorials/http-the-protocol-every-web-developer-must-know-part-1--net-31177 (a bit more technical)
  • https://http.cat/ (an amusing site that might help you to understand HTTP status codes ;)

Fantastic! Lets go get some data!!!

Warning: this is often much more easily said than done. The more you practice using different tools to access different sites the better you will get at it. Luckily, you will get a lot of practice doing this during AT2! Make sure that you encourage everyone on you team to work on this data collection phase, as it is important that you build up your skills in this key area if you are going to be a successful data scientist!

Part a: RSDMX - interfacing with XML based data repositiories

Here we will work through one method for using an API to interface with OECD data using the rsdmx package. It would be a very good idea for you to try out a couple of other methods to build up your familiarity with the types of things you might have to do (and how it can go wrong).

You will probably have to install this package using the install.packages("rsdmx") command, and load it. Try running ?rsdmx and you will find out that the help for this package is pretty useless. However, there is a vignette associated with this package (how do I know that? Can you work out what function I use to see all the vignettes that I have on my computer?)

Lets have a look at that vignette. If you run these commands in your terminal then the vignette should open in RStudio:

library(rsdmx)

NB. You can check out the docs with this command vignette("quickstart", package="rsdmx")

You can find out about all of the SDMX service providers that rsdmx can access via this call

providers <- getSDMXServiceProviders()
as.data.frame(providers)

Ooooo - lots of goodies in there. If you do the call without the forcing as.data.frame then you can even see the websites that get accessed (beware though - that is a fairly unreadable report so you have to pore over it in detail to understand what it is - you can try running str(providers) to find out more about the dataset just be prepared for a lot of output!)

Right-o. The OECD makes its data available in SDMX via the interface provided at this page: https://data.oecd.org/ Go and have a look at the site. What can you find out? There are actually quite a few ways in which you can download OECD data from this site. Make sure you understand who the OECD are, and what types of interfaces they provide (not all are SDMX interfaces).

SDMX stands for Statistical Data and Metadata Exchange. It is a widely used standard for economic and population data providers. Queries to the provider via the API may be of two major types: data itself or description of data (metadata). So. We have decided we want to get some data from the OECD. Here is a very useful page that I found by doing a bit of browsing of the OECD data site: https://data.oecd.org/api/sdmx-ml-documentation/ (can you find it by following links from the top page?) Have a bit of a read of it, and try working out how you could interface with this API using the rsdmx package using that documentation.

So here is an interesting screenshot from that page

What does that mean about how we need to define the URL that we need in the call to rsdmx? (Which of you have read the help page for readSDMX alredy? Try looking that one up using the R help functionality.)

So. The first thing we need to do is find a database on the website that we are interested in. Try and find the link to the catalogue on the above webpage and have a look at what is available. So, for accessing OECD data, this page tells us that we minimally need:

  • a dataset identifier
  • a filter expression
  • an agency name

The optional parameters listed below on that page (find them for an exercise) then tell you how you can filter the data to sub-intervals, or access other features in the database.

I am going to have a look at some data on employment rate vs educational attainment: http://www.oecd-ilibrary.org/education/data/education-at-a-glance/educational-attainment-and-labour-force-status_889e8641-en. Have a bit of a look at this page. What can you see that will help you use rsdmx? One thing to try out is finding this page of data from the root OECD data page (https://data.oecd.org/), which is well worth exploring anyway!

So first things first: I need to find the dataset identifier. It is EAG_NEAC. Can you see how I worked that out? (Hint: click on the data link.) The dataset will actually show you precisely what command to run if you want to download the data. I have decided just to download the data for Australia (as otherwise it gets very big!) You can filter the dataset for country and many other things. You should explore the relevant page until you can work out how I generated this link:

So what on earth did that just do? Try looking at the data - what format is it in? (Beware - you will get a lot of data if you just enter eag.neac in your R console, but try it out anyway! See what you get :) Your response is likely to be: Eeek!

Anyone at your table recognise this output format? It is XML. SDMX is an API built for this data standard. These days there are ones for JSON etc. too. You will need to explore and work out what format the API you are trying to deal with returns its data in and then interface with it as you can. Often this will require quite a bit of web searching, and then finessing of R packages that you find on the web.

(Remember this: Data science is often more of an art than a science. You are likely to spend most of your time trying to work out how to get data, and then get it into the format you need - the statistical analysis is often the easy part!)

Part b: httr

Lying somewhere between a full data API service, and all out webscraping is the httr package (which is basically a wrapper for curl - ignore that comment if you dont know what I am talking about!) It is not in the core tidyverse, but is designed to be compatible with it. If you dont already have it then you will need to make sure you install it! (using install.packages("httr")).

How does it work? Try typing in ?httr and do a bit of exploring of the help pages that come up Note that there are demos for using this package with various OAuth protocols: four for 1.0 (linkedin, twitter, vimeo, and yahoo) and eight for 2.0 (azure, facebook, github, google, linkedin, reddit, yahoo, and yelp). That is a LOT of sites where you might be looking for data! A pretty useful looking package eh? So how does it work?

There are three very useful vignettes provided with the httr package:

  • https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/httr/vignettes/quickstart.html
  • https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/httr/vignettes/api-packages.html
  • https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/httr/vignettes/secrets.html

as well as the httr manual:

  • https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/httr/httr.pdf

Here I will reproduce the github_api function Hadley Wickham provides in the API packages vignette (above). It is a really nice example of best practice from the Master. As an important note, until you are really proficient using APIs I strongly recommend you stick with the GET verb, that way you are unlikely to get into trouble or make yourself very unpopular with the providers of the API! For simplicity and demonstration purposes, we are starting this example with an API that doesnt require authentication.

The function provides the following tasks:

  1. Sends a GET request to github to find out about Hadleys repos
  2. Indicates whether the request returns a json or xml format
  3. If in a json format, parses the json into text
  4. Manually returns the response into an S3 object (check out Advanced R https://adv-r.hadley.nz/s3.html if you want to learn more about S3 objects.)

Make sure you understand what each part of the code below is doing.

library(httr)
library(jsonlite)
## 
## Attaching package: 'jsonlite'
## The following object is masked from 'package:purrr':
## 
##     flatten
github_api <- function(path) {
  url <- modify_url("https://api.github.com", path = path)
  
  resp <- GET(url)
  if (http_type(resp) != "application/json") {
    stop("API did not return json", call. = FALSE)
  }
  
  parsed <- jsonlite::fromJSON(content(resp, "text"), simplifyVector = FALSE)
  
  structure(
    list(
      content = parsed,
      path = path,
      response = resp
    ),
    class = "github_api"
  )
}

print.github_api <- function(x, ...) {
  cat("<GitHub ", x$path, ">\n", sep = "")
  str(x$content)
  invisible(x)
}

Alternatively, in this instance, you can automatically parse the json file into a named list using the default parser:

library(httr)
github_api2 <- function(path) {
  url <- modify_url("https://api.github.com", path = path)
  
  resp <- GET(url)
  if (http_type(resp) != "application/json") {
    stop("API did not return json", call. = FALSE)
  }
  
  str(content(resp, "parsed"))
}

Option 4: Scrape some data

Finally sometimes you will find data on the web that is not directly downloadable as a spreadsheet or providing sensible API endpoints.

(BTW: if there is an alternative to this method then it is most polite to use it, some people get rather cranky if you use the method we are about to discuss on a domain where they have provided interfacing capabilities via an API. It can also be directly forbidden and possibly illegal to webscrape according to terms and conditions of some sites so beware!)

In this scenario, we can webscrape, which returns unstructured HTML data. There are some great tools in R for doing this. We are going to discuss rvest here, as it is designed to work with magrittr, so is part of the tidyverse! Here are some good pages on how to use it:

  • https://blog.rstudio.com/2014/11/24/rvest-easy-web-scraping-with-r/
  • https://www.analyticsvidhya.com/blog/2017/03/beginners-guide-on-web-scraping-in-r-using-rvest-with-hands-on-knowledge/
library(rvest)
## 
## Attaching package: 'rvest'
## The following object is masked from 'package:readr':
## 
##     guess_encoding

Ok. Lets get started. You should probably start by reading the vignette on selector gadget. Run this command to do that: vignette("selectorgadget",package="rvest") (NB: make sure you have rvest installed first!) This vignette is very good, and will explain to you how I got the line of code below:

html <- read_html("https://www.uts.edu.au/about/university/facts-figures-and-rankings")
UTS.data <- html_nodes(html, "table:nth-child(5), th")

So that set of commands goes and gets the data about UTS that is stored on the page in the link. Go and have a look at the page! Try using selector gadget until you get the text that I have listed in the quotes above. (Look at the vignette if you are having trouble.)

The trouble is the table format makes this fairly hard to process. (You can try, but I gave up ;) So, for example, we can look at this item:

UTS.data
## {xml_nodeset (27)}
##  [1] <table><tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Course type</th>\n\t\t\t<th>2018</th>\n\t\t\t< ...
##  [2] <th>Course type</th>
##  [3] <th>2018</th>
##  [4] <th>2019</th>
##  [5] <th>2020</th>

##  [9] <th>2020</th>

## [12] <th>Post<br>\n\t\t\tgraduate<br>\n\t\t\tcourse<br>\n\t\t\twork</th>
## [13] <th>UNDER<br>\n\t\t\tgraduate,<br>\n\t\t\tENABLING<br>\n\t\t\tAND<br>\n\ ...
## [14] <th>Total</th>
## [15] <th>Enrolled Faculty</th>
## [16] <th>Higher<br>\n\t\t\tdegree<br>\n\t\t\tresearch</th>
## [17] <th>Post<br>\n\t\t\tgraduate<br>\n\t\t\tCourse<br>\n\t\t\twork</th>
## [18] <th>UNDER<br>\n\t\t\tgraduate,<br>\n\t\t\tENABLING<br>\n\t\t\tAND<br>\n\ ...

## [20] <th>Course type</th>

We have all the info we need, but we are going to need to do some magic with regular expressions to get this into one big table. Probably more than you want to explore at this point in time! (Although feel free to try and do it later!)

Luckily, there is another set of functions in rvest that make this very easy indeed. Here we are asking for rvest to extract the data from the first table on the page.

UTS.table <- html_node(html, "table")

What do you think we have in our data now? Lets have a look:

UTS.table
## {html_node}
## <table>
## [1] <tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Course type</th>\n\t\t\t<th>2018</th>\n\t\t\t<th>2019< ...

We can manipulate that data into a vector form too:

html_table(UTS.table)

Oooh yeah. Thats what we want.

You will need to just keep playing with this to build up some knowledge about how to do it. If you have a background in web dev then you might find this set of methods very nice indeed for getting data!

Can we plot our dataset? For that we need to get it in tidy form. We need to turn the chr strings into integers, which is going to require removing the commas, and then coercing to an int. Also, the data is currently in a wide format. We need to get it into a long format:

tidyUTS <- html_table(UTS.table) %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c(`2018`,`2019`,`2020`), names_to = "year", values_to = "enrolled") %>% 
  mutate(enrolled = parse_number(enrolled), year = parse_integer(year))
tidyUTS

Can we plot it now? (removing the Total from Course type and formatting the x and y axis labels)

tidyUTS %>% 
  filter(`Course type` != "Total") %>% 
  ggplot() + 
  geom_line(aes(x =`year`, y =`enrolled`, color =`Course type`)) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::comma) +
  scale_x_continuous(n.breaks = 3)

Cool - that was actually rather easier than you might have expected after playing with rsdmx ;)

Summary

So web scraping might seem easier than using APIs, but it often involves a lot of wrangling, and is likely to annoy the people hosting a website if they have provided an API interface for you. Good to know how to do it, but be careful not to use it just because you can.
